{{Refimprove|date=September 2015}}
{{Thermoreg}} '''Thermolabile''' refers to a substance which is subject to destruction, [[chemical decomposition|decomposition]], or change in response to [[heat]]. This term is often used to describe [[biochemical]] substances.
For example, many bacterial [[exotoxin]]s are thermolabile and can be easily inactivated by the application of moderate heat. [[Enzyme]]s are also thermolabile and lose their activity when the temperature rises. Loss of activity in such toxins and enzymes is likely due to change in the three-dimensional structure of the toxin [[protein]] during exposure to heat. In [[pharmaceutical]] compounds, heat generated during grinding may lead to degradation of thermolabile compounds.
This is of particular use in testing [[gene]] function.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tan|first1=G|last2=Chen|first2=M|last3=Foote|first3=C|last4=Tan|first4=C|title=Temperature-sensitive mutations made easy: generating conditional mutations by using temperature-sensitive inteins that function within different temperature ranges.|journal=Genetics|date=September 2009|volume=183|issue=1|pages=13–22|pmid=19596904|doi=10.1534/genetics.109.104794|pmc=2746138}}</ref> This is done by intentionally creating [[mutant]]s which are thermolabile. Growth below the [[permissive temperature]] allows normal protein function, while increasing the temperature above the permissive temperature ablates activity, likely by [[Denaturation (biochemistry)|denaturing]] the protein.
Thermolabile [[enzymes]] are also studied for their applications in [[DNA replication]] techniques, such as [[PCR]], where [[thermostable]] enzymes are necessary for proper DNA replication. Enzyme function at higher temperatures may be enhanced with [[trehalose]], which opens up the possibility of using normally thermolabile enzymes in DNA replication.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Thermostabilization and thermoactivation of thermolabile enzymes by trehalose and its application for the synthesis of full length cDNA|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=95|pages=520-524|doi=10.1073/pnas.95.2.520|date=January 1998|first1=PIERO |last1=CARNINCI|display-authors=etal|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/a4fd/1cc88fe64b474484f1d8d2910ed93053cb70.pdf|pmc=18452}}</ref>
